00:00:33.090 --> 00:00:35.800
In Canada we have four seasons.

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:39.920
We have Winter when the snow flies and it's
really really cold.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:46.100
We have Spring when everything starts to grow
and the trees get leaves back on them again.

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:51.239
We have Summer when everything grows like
crazy, that means it grows a lot!

00:00:51.239 --> 00:00:53.489
And it's really really hot.

00:00:53.489 --> 00:00:56.520
And we have Fall or Autumn.

00:00:56.520 --> 00:00:59.149
It has two names in English.

00:00:59.149 --> 00:01:05.109
Generally we use the term, "Fall" and I think
"Fall" became popular because in the, in the

00:01:05.109 --> 00:01:06.990
Fall leaves fall off the trees.

00:01:06.990 --> 00:01:11.719
So you'll see in the path behind me there's
just all kinds of leaves that have fallen

00:01:11.719 --> 00:01:13.630
from the trees.

00:01:13.630 --> 00:01:20.299
In the Fall trees turn from their normal green
colour to brown, red, orange, yellow, and

00:01:20.299 --> 00:01:23.710
all the shades in between and it's really
a beautiful season to be outside.

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:31.700
So in English we have three words to describe
the forest.

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:33.340
We have, "forest".

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:34.670
We have, "woods".

00:01:34.670 --> 00:01:35.899
And we have, "bush".

00:01:35.899 --> 00:01:40.009
In my area of Ontario, Canada we generally
use the term, "bush".

00:01:40.009 --> 00:01:45.700
If I was to say to someone, "I'm going out
to the forest to go for a walk."

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:49.880
They might look at me funny, because we don't
use the word, "forest" a lot in this area.

00:01:49.880 --> 00:01:53.890
But if I said, "I'm going out to the bush
to go for a walk."

00:01:53.890 --> 00:01:55.909
They would understand what I'm talking about.

