00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:48.260
So there's three main reasons why you might
come out to the woods, or the forest.

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:51.769
You might be someone who is a avid hunter.

00:02:51.769 --> 00:02:57.030
That's someone who really likes hunting for
animals, maybe with a bow and arrow.

00:02:57.030 --> 00:03:02.060
It's possible that you just like to go on
a hike or a nature walk.

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:07.879
And it's also possible that you're coming
out to the forest to cut down trees for firewood.

00:03:07.879 --> 00:03:14.720
In Canada we still have a lot of people that
use wood to heat their houses in the winter.

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:21.360
So it's pretty common to come out to the forest
or the woods to cut down trees for firewood.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:24.060
Usually when you do that you have a chainsaw.

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:26.780
I'll put a picture up here of a chainsaw.

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:32.590
And you have what we call a log splitter in
order to split the pieces of wood into firewood,

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:37.379
and then that firewood is used in a wood burning
stove to heat their home.

00:03:37.379 --> 00:03:41.910
So there's really two kinds of trees that
you'll find in the forest.

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:44.049
There's deciduous trees.

00:03:44.049 --> 00:03:50.750
Those are trees where the leaves turn colour
and they fall off in the Autumn or Fall.

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:55.110
Deciduous trees are trees like, maple, or
oak, or poplar.

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:58.160
There's also coniferous trees.

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:03.560
Coniferous trees are trees that have needles
instead of leaves, and they stay green year

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:04.560
round.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:07.360
The needles don't fall off in the winter.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:14.280
A few examples of coniferous trees are trees
like spruce, or pine, or cedar.

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.840
